        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Imaging: This short-baseline configuration is imperative for the science goal of mapping the outer debris belt of the Fomalhaut system to detect deviations from azimuthal symmetry. Our only empirical reference for the physical size of such a structure is the HST scattered light images that show a ~50% dip in optical belt brightness at PA=331 degrees.  The projected size of this gap is ~2" (15 AU), but in the deprojected frame this corresponds to 6.5" (50 AU).  The projection effects can be ascertained by eye in Fig. 1 (top panel), which shows that as a 25 AU structure is placed closer to either ansa of the belt (i.e. along the major axis), the projected size diminishes.  Therefore to map a 25 AU structure along the minor axis of the belt where projection effects are negligible we need to recover angular scales corresponding to ~3".  But to recover the HST-detected gap we wish to resolve &lt;2".   Only the shortest baselines offered at Band 6 are capable of resolving the larger scales without the ACA.  The Fomalhaut outer belt subtends a region roughly 30" x 40" on the sky, requiring at least a 7-point mosaic to cover the area of the large belt given the primary beam size of 22" at the frequency of Band 6.  The smallest angular scale of these observations is set to resolve 1.6" on the sky, which approximately matches the Band 7, Cycle 0 observations, and thereby will permit a comparison of features at the same scales for the two different observing bands.   We note that the Keplerian velocity at 140 AU corresponds to 0.1" motion per year.  Therefore, for azimuthal features oriented near the belt minor axis (i.e. without projection effects), these proposed short-baseline data could detection the orbital motion of belt features over the next two decades.

Sensitivity: At the 1.6" (12 AU) resolution of the most compact configuration in Band 6, the peak flux in the disk is 1.5 mJy/beam in the disk ansae (projected major axis), but is nearly an order of magnitude fainter along the front and back of the disk (projected minor axis).  In order to reliably recover the ~50% beam-to-beam flux variations that are expected on the basis of the scattered light imaging, and to recover the large-scale flux distribution in the disk, we require a signal-to-noise ratio of 10 per beam around the entire disk circumference, resulting in an rms sensitivity of less than 10 uJy/beam.  Given the imaging constraints, we require 30 minutes per pointing, or a total of about 3 hours, to reach this sensitivity across the mosaic field (the "desired sensitivity per pointing" has been adjusted to account for the overlapping mosaic fields, as suggested by the knowledgebase article about user-specified mosaics).  

Correlator: Since this project is limited by continuum sensitivity, we configure the correlator for the maximum bandwidth.  We include a low-resolution line observation configured to detect CO at 1.3 km/s resolution, which would easily resolve the anticipated 7 km/s linewidth of the Fomalhaut outer belt.  The opportunity for serendipitous CO detection does not reduce the aggregate continuum sensitivity.
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
