            <prj:justificationText>	Imaging: The goals of the high-resolution configuration are to resolve structure in the outer belt at scales smaller than 12 AU, and to resolve the basic size and geometry of the inner belt for the first time.  Detailed SED modeling predicts that the inner belt is confined to a narrow ring from 8 to 15 AU (1"-2" in radius).  Because of the relatively large inclination of the Fomalhaut system to the line of sight, separating the ring from the bright photosphere of the central star requires sub-arcsecond spatial resolution.  Due to the tradeoff between angular resolution and sensitivity, we propose an angular resolution of 0.35" (2.7 AU), which is sufficient to resolve the basic structure of the disk separate from the star, but low enough to minimize the sensitivity requirement.  Because our science goals also involve resolving the outer disk, we again opt for a 7-point mosaic to cover the roughly 30x40 arcsecond field subtended by the Fomalhaut debris disk.  On their own, these observations would suffer from severe spatial filtering in the outer disk; however, in combination with the compact configuration observations requested we are able to reconstruct a complete image of the system at high fidelity (see Fig. 2, bottom panel).  Recalling that the Keplerian velocity at 140 AU corresponds to 0.1" motion per year.  Therefore, for azimuthal features oriented near the belt minor axis (i.e. without projection effects), these proposed extended configuration data could detect the orbital motion of compact belt features (if detected in Cycle 2) by reobserving the belt with a high-resolution configuration in Cycle 5.  

	Sensitivity: The time request is motivated by a need to achieve our signal-to-noise goals across both the inner and outer disk.  The peak flux at 0.35" resolution is a mere 0.8 mJy/beam, and typical values in the outer ring are 25 uJy/beam.  In order to resolve the outer ring, therefore, we require an rms noise of less than 10 uJy/beam, which can be achieved in 6 hours total (50 minutes per pointing) of a 7-pointing mosaic at Band 6.  

	Correlator: We select an identical correlator and tuning setup as for the compact array configuration in order to best combine the two data sets.  We configure one baseband on the CO(2-1) transition at 1.3 km/s resolution to enable CO detection without loss of the continuum sensitivity that drives the time request.  
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
    </prj:ScienceGoal>
