    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>Among exoplanetary systems, Fomalhaut stands out as the only known system where an exoplanet potentially crosses through the system's Kuiper Belt.  Fomalhaut therefore represents a unique opportunity to directly observe an epoch of evolution that could correspond to the LHB in our solar system. Fomalhaut is also one of the closest exoplanetary systems, and its dust structures and their evolution can be mapped in unprecedented detail.  ALMA is ideally suited to create such a map because over the 30" x 40" Fomalhaut field it detects structure at high resolution and with repeatable fidelity over decade timescales.  We propose creating a detailed atlas of the entire system in Band 6 using both the compact and extended arrays, mapping belt structure on 0.35" (2.7 AU) to 10" (77 AU) scales.  These data will resolve the inner dust belt for the first time. Its size and asymmetries will help constrain Fomalhaut b's periastron distance, and assess if a second planet could exist in the 10 AU region.  The detailed ALMA map of the outer belt will test for substructure such as the belt gap recently identified with HST, and address the questions of Fomalhaut b's interaction with the belt.</prp:abstract>
